    <text>
        <body>
            <head>2. Telegram From the Embassy in <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libya</placeName> to the Department of State<note n="1" place="foot"
                    type="source" xml:id="d2fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign
                    Policy File, D770021–0691. Secret; <gloss target="#t_Exdis_1">Exdis</gloss>.
                    Sent for information to Cairo, Khartoum, and Tunis.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Tripoli</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1977-01-20T08:37:00+00:00">January 20, 1977, 0837Z</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>74. Subject: Egyptian Ambassador’s Comments on <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="rec80ZRVkTQfLW60o">Egyptian/Libyan Relations</rs>.</p>
            <p>1. Summary. Egyptian Amb in Tripoli views future of relations with <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> pessimistically and with some
                foreboding. <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> plans to
                continue and even step up pressure on <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> regime.</p>
            <p>2. During meeting January 19 Egyptian Ambassador Tuhmai commented extensively on what
                he described as bad and deteriorating relations between his country and <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>. Ambassador reiterated that
                Egyptian complaints against <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                included <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> sponsorship of
                the anti-<persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName>/<persName
                    corresp="rec2oKBlgVlF3gmdN">Nasserite</persName> organization in <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> and <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName>, <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> sponsored sabotage activities in
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and the frozen Egyptian
                accounts in <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> banks
                amounting to some 17 million [garble—dinars?]. The Ambassador observed that the
                Libyans are reorganizing the <persName corresp="rec2oKBlgVlF3gmdN"
                    >Nasserite</persName> organization among Egyptians in <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> and seeking to recruit young
                Egyptian students to expand it. Nasserites were responsible for sabotage in
                    <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> and might be behind
                current rioting.</p>
            <p>3. Ambassador said he felt somewhat insecure in Tripoli though active surveillance
                had decreased. He added, however, that the possibility of Egyptian and/or <placeName
                    corresp="recT1ZO3iDiD8XTeX">Sudanese</placeName> military intervention in
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> was still possible
                provided there was a suitable internal situation to warrant it. He felt that in such
                a case Egyptian Embassy would be subject to open attack. Even under current
                circumstances the possibility of a <gloss target="#t_LARG_1">
                    <orgName corresp="rec0DjV1UIFMpMgBG">LARG</orgName>
                </gloss> inspired demonstration could not be ruled out. Ambassador claimed his
                cypher communications system now insecure because of <pb facs="0024" n="3"
                    xml:id="pg_3"/> possible <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                    >Libyan</placeName> penetration with <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3"
                    >Soviet</placeName> aid. Accordingly, he was under instructions from Cairo to
                use only couriers.</p>
            <p>4. Tuhmai saw little possibility for mediation noting that <placeName
                    corresp="rec42COeVy9m2xFQ3">Guinea</placeName>’s Sekou Toure’s attempt had
                failed because Libyans had refused to agree to discussion of outstanding problems.
                    <persName corresp="rec1cjdjaVRK3s2qt">Tito</persName>, currently in Tripoli, was
                unlikely to try again this area having already failed once.</p>
            <p>5. Ambassador views <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> as
                feeling increasingly insecure. He tells visiting dignitaries that <persName
                    corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> intends to kill him. He has growing
                concern over what he sees as encirclement by <placeName corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW"
                    >Egypt</placeName>, <placeName corresp="recT1ZO3iDiD8XTeX">Sudan</placeName>,
                    <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> and possibly <placeName
                    corresp="recGkuSlDiu6KVzHj">Tunisia</placeName>. Policy of the Egyptian
                Government, according to Tuhami, will be to do whatever possible to increase this
                nervousness. Accordingly, former <orgName corresp="recy36bQ9XxVFvhb1">RCC</orgName>
                member Muyhayshi is to be unleashed again in the near future over Egyptian radio
                which now reaches every home in Tripoli. Also <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip"
                    >Sadat</persName> himself will make further public statements regarding
                    <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>’s evil and irrational
                activities.</p>
            <p>6. Though charitably suggesting <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> perhaps unaware of everything bad that happened in
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>, Tuhmai doubted
                possibility of ever reaching a viable understanding with him. He suggested <gloss
                    target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> “should get rid of him.” I replied that <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> found <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> very
                difficult indeed but certainly would not rpt not interfere in internal <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> affairs.</p>
            <p>7. In response to a query as to with whom among present <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> leaders <placeName
                    corresp="rec8KXzhReLUudAMW">Egypt</placeName> might possibly work, Ambassador
                responded that his Embassy had recently had vague and indirect approaches from Prime
                Minister <persName corresp="recU4berhukXjdZ1F">Jallud</persName> whom they regarded
                as tough and crude but reasonably open. At the same time if separation between
                eastern and western <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                developed, Egyptians thought that <orgName corresp="recy36bQ9XxVFvhb1">RCC</orgName>
                member Kharoubi might well become the leader of the eastern portion and was someone
                with whom they might also work.</p>
            <p>8. Tuhami spoke more than he listened but was interested in extent of <gloss
                    target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> support for <rs type="topic" corresp="rec1GiKVfLPrlIGzK">C–130</rs>
                maintenance. I explained status of <orgName corresp="recmZgvBPFsMrNgrR"
                    >Lockheed</orgName> technical group and basics of <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss>/<placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> policy. We agreed
                to keep in touch. He claimed to have discussed <placeName
                    corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> policy at length with President
                    <persName corresp="recIigdM8sR9uq1Ip">Sadat</persName> and <gloss
                    target="#t_FonMin_1">FonMin</gloss>
                <persName corresp="recepwADCEWxlTqkQ">Fahmy</persName> during recent consultations
                in Cairo. I leave it to my colleagues in Cairo to assess the authority of his
                somewhat fearsome predictions for the future.</p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName>
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Carle</hi>
                    </persName>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
